msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "2.The Salt March: India 1930"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:69
msgid ""
"Forced to pay inflated prices for the salt which keeps them alive, thousands "
"of Indians follow one man on the long road to victory and independence."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "Right against might"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:73
msgid ""
"The1882 Salt Act prohibited the people of India, while under British rule, "
"from collecting, producing or selling salt. The poor suffered most as they "
"could not afford to buy the heavily taxed salt, a mineral vital for human "
"metabolism in hot, humid climates. Those who broke the law were imprisoned."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:75
msgid ""
"[Mahatma "
"Gandhi](https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2019/10/mahatma-gandhi-150-anniversary-of-birth/) "
"left his ashram in Sabarmati on 12 March 1930 with 78 followers, to be "
"joined by tens of thousands of others along the [240 mile "
"march](https://scholarblogs.emory.edu/postcolonialstudies/2014/06/20/gandhis-salt-march-to-dandi/) "
"to the Arabian Sea."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:77
msgid ""
"By lifting salt from the ground in the coastal town of Dandi on 6th April, "
"he openly defied British law. Gandhi had mobilised the satyagrahi, a "
"philosophy of truth-focused, non-violent non-cooperation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:79
msgid ""
"As part of the Civil Disobedience Movement, thousands more followed Gandhi's "
"lead, with salt being made, bought and sold illegally all across "
"India. 60,000 peaceful protestors were arrested, including Gandhi himself, "
"which raised further global awareness of the situation in India."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:81
msgid ""
"The Salt March and the ensuing Civil Disobedience Movement shook the "
"foundations of the British Empire, while providing a turning point on the "
"road to Indian independence in 1947. It was a simple yet defiant act of "
"civil disobedience by people of conviction and courage, taking a stand "
"against a giant world power."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:83
msgid ""
"![Gandhi collecting salt on the Gujarat "
"coast](/assets/uploads/7b1b080b-8704-440c-971a-0a24c02735a2.jpg)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Gandhi collecting salt on the Gujarat coast. April 1930. Public domain.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "3. Segregation Defiance: USA 1955-56"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:89
msgid ""
"When an African American schoolgirl is ordered to give up her seat to a "
"white woman, the abolitionists provide her with the strength to stay where "
"she is."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "History Had Me Glued to My Seat"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:93
msgid ""
"At the age of 15, schoolgirl [Claudette "
"Colvin](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V3NvXzFOb6w) became the first "
"African American to refuse to give up her seat to a white woman on a bus in "
"Montgomery, Alabama."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:95
msgid ""
"Colvin stated she felt the hands of abolitionists [Harriet "
"Tubman](https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/harriet-tubman) "
"and [Sojourner Truth](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q-HfiryNoXY) holding "
"her down. She was dragged from the bus and subjected to sexist and racist "
"behaviour before being arrested and held in an adult jail."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:97
msgid ""
"Following the arrest of [Rosa "
"Parks](https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/rosa-parks) "
"nine months later for the same action, the Women’s Political Council (WPC), "
"a group of black women working for civil rights, circulated 50,000 flyers "
"calling for a boycott of the Montgomery bus system. As news spread of the "
"boycott, African American leaders across Montgomery began to lend their "
"support."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:99
msgid ""
"From December 5, 1955 to December 20, 1956, approximately 40,000 African "
"Americans refused to travel on Montgomery buses. Although many chose to "
"walk, carpools were organised, with the city’s African American taxi drivers "
"charging the same price as the bus fare for African American riders."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:101
msgid ""
"The protestors were determined to continue until the city met with their "
"demands, which included the hiring of black bus drivers and a first-come "
"first-seated policy. Ultimately a group of five Montgomery women sued the "
"city in the U.S. District Court, seeking to have the segregation laws "
"totally invalidated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:103
msgid ""
"In December 1956, the US Supreme Court ruled the end of segregated "
"buses. The legal case, which ended the boycott, was partially built on the "
"testimony of [Claudette "
"Colvin](https://www.npr.org/2009/03/15/101719889/before-rosa-parks-there-was-claudette-colvin?t=1593952359137)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:105
msgid ""
"The Montgomery bus boycott was an incredibly brave action and is regarded as "
"the first large-scale U.S. demonstration against segregation and was pivotal "
"in the Civil Rights Movement, itself a successful and hugely significant "
"example of the power of civil disobedience."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:106
#, no-wrap
msgid "4. Wave Hill Walk Off: Australia 1966 - 1975"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:109
msgid ""
"Two hundred people turn their back on abuse and move to settle on "
"traditional land. They refuse to leave, demanding the rightful return of the "
"land to the indigenous people."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "Without the land we are nothing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:113
msgid ""
"Gurindji tribal elder [Vincent "
"Lingiari](https://australianstogether.org.au/discover/australian-history/wave/) "
"led two hundred pastoral workers away from the privately owned Wave Hill "
"cattle station in the Northern Territory, as a protest against low pay, "
"poverty and [decades of "
"abuse](https://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-19/the-untold-story-being-the-1966-wave-hill-walk-off/7764524). "
"The ‘Walk Off Mob’ formed a new settlement at Daguragu, refusing an order to "
"vacate. The strike lasted seven years."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:115
msgid ""
"Lingiari’s continued lobbying of politicians galvanised the strike and "
"gained support from non-indigenous Australians. It was the precursor to "
"lands rights legislation almost ten years later when, in 1975, 3300 square "
"kilometers of Australian land was the first returned to the Gurindji tribe."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:117
msgid ""
"In 1976, [The Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) "
"Act](https://www.nma.gov.au/defining-moments/resources/aboriginal-land-rights-act#:~:text=In%20December%201976%20the%20federal,traditional%20ownership%20could%20be%20proven.) "
"was signed, allowing indigenous people to claim traditional and spiritual "
"land."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:119
msgid "A workers’ rights action resulting in a land rights victory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "5. The Sip-in: USA 1966"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:123
msgid ""
"Four men walk into a bar and ask to be served. Sevice is denied because they "
"are gay — the men risk arrest to ensure their story is reported and shared."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:124
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are homosexuals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:127
msgid ""
"In 1966 New York City, serving alcohol to homosexuals was illegal. Under a "
"disorderly conduct statute, city ‘cleanups’ encouraged the closure of bars "
"frequented by gays and the arrest of homosexual customers by way of police "
"entrapment. Many lives were destroyed as a result."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:129
msgid ""
"[Dick Leitsch](https://makinggayhistory.com/podcast/dick-leitsch/), a "
"pivotal figure in the fight for gay rights, accompanied by three friends "
"from the [Mattachine "
"Society](https://www.magellantv.com/articles/the-mattachine-society-lgbtq-history)—John "
"Timmins, Randy Wicker and CraigRodwell—entered Julius’ bar in Greenwich "
"Village, declared themselves homosexuals and asked to be served. This is "
"thought to be the first organised act of civil disobedience by gay people."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:131
msgid ""
"Service was denied and the incident was widely reported in the press. Within "
"a year, New York State courts ended the practice of using gay patronage as "
"an excuse for revoking liquor licences; thus opening the way for licenced "
"gay bars."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:133
msgid ""
"Leitsch’s further actions were instrumental in putting an end to entrapment "
"while encouraging legal challenges to charges based solely on police "
"testimony."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:135
msgid ""
"![Dick Leitsch, "
"1966](/assets/uploads/fa9c2130-8fbe-420c-9e65-6c41d81a2eea.jpg)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Dick Leitsch, 1966. Photographer unknown.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:139
msgid ""
"Influenced by the sit-ins at segregated lunch counters by black civil rights "
"protestors, this was a brilliant example of how the non-violent, courteous "
"action of four brave individuals led to societal change and the reframing of "
"public understanding."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:140
#, no-wrap
msgid "6. Navy-Culebra Protests: Puerto Rico 1970"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:143
msgid ""
"As a world superpower destroys a tiny island with bombs and bullets, "
"undeterred inhabitants refuse to surrender the fight to reclaim their home."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:144
#, no-wrap
msgid "Culebra should be for Culebra"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:147
msgid ""
"In 1970, "
"[Culebra](https://nvdatabase.swarthmore.edu/content/puerto-ricans-expel-united-states-navy-culebra-island-1970-1974) "
"islanders undertook a series of protests against the United States Navy for "
"its use of the island for military training exercises."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:149
msgid ""
"The Navy expropriated 2000 of the island’s 7000 acres for bombing "
"practice. Homes were torn down, and targets erected. A three mile exclusion "
"zone was set around the island, making prisoners of the island's 700 "
"inhabitants. Little fishing remained and any cattle were grazed on navy "
"owned land."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:151
msgid ""
"[LIFE](https://books.google.ca/books?id=lVUEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA40-IA5#v=onepage&q&f=false) "
"magazine reported ‘the crunch of 500-pound bombs...the whine of jets, "
"echoing machine gun fire, screaming rockets and the triple-throated boom of "
"naval shells.’ Protestors stated that the bombing missions, which often "
"occurred seven days a week, placed Culebra in a ‘[deplorable "
"situation](https://voices.revealdigital.org/?a=d&d=BCHDEAIG19710301.1.4&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN---------------1).’"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:153
msgid ""
"Unwilling to withdraw claims to the whole island, protestors built a chapel "
"in just three days on Flamingo Beach, a restricted, major target area, using "
"only crude tools. US Marshals ordered them to leave but they refused and six "
"people were arrested. Six days later, the navy demolished the chapel."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:155
msgid ""
"Protesters illegally occupied restricted areas, including Flamingo Beach, "
"remaining there for several weeks. Those who needed new homes squatted on "
"Navy land, which was also used in the creation of sports areas and "
"graveyards."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:157
msgid ""
"President of the Puerto Rican Independence Party and protest leader, Rubén "
"Berríos, along with thirteen others, was sentenced to three months in a "
"Puerto Rico prison for civil disobedience and trespassing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:159
msgid ""
"In 1974, all political parties in Puerto Rico called for the US Navy to "
"cease operations and leave the island. Finally, in 1974, President Nixon "
"ordered the Navy to leave the island, which they did in December 1975."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2020-11-03-civil-disobedience-examples.md:161
msgid ""
"Another example of a few hundred brave people standing firm in the shadow of "
"a world superpower."
msgstr ""

